#. HTML: </p><h1>
#. VAR: sotānudhanasuttaṃ (bj)
msgctxt "an4.191:0.3"
msgid "191. Sotānugatasutta "
msgstr "191. Followed by Ear "

# NOTE: See BB’s note on variants here. Note that our text gives the BJ reading as sotānudhana, whereas BB says Ce reads sotānudhata. Also note that, in addition to the sources cited by BB, the Tika and Pe both support anugata. Anudhata in fact doesn’t appear to occur anywhere.
#. HTML: </h1></div><p>
#. REF: sc1
#. VAR: Sotānugatānaṃ → sotānudhanānaṃ (bj)
msgctxt "an4.191:1.1"
msgid "“Sotānugatānaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ, vacasā paricitānaṃ, manasānupekkhitānaṃ, diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhānaṃ cattāro ānisaṃsā pāṭikaṅkhā. "
msgstr "“Mendicants, you can expect four benefits when the teachings have been followed by ear, reinforced by recitation, examined by the mind, and well comprehended theoretically. "

msgctxt "an4.191:1.2"
msgid "Katame cattāro? "
msgstr "What four? "

#. HTML: </p><p>
msgctxt "an4.191:1.3"
msgid "Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu dhammaṃ pariyāpuṇāti—"
msgstr "Take a mendicant who memorizes the teaching—"

msgctxt "an4.191:1.4"
msgid "suttaṃ, geyyaṃ, veyyākaraṇaṃ, gāthaṃ, udānaṃ, itivuttakaṃ, jātakaṃ, abbhutadhammaṃ, vedallaṃ. "
msgstr "statements, songs, discussions, verses, inspired exclamations, legends, stories of past lives, amazing stories, and classifications. "

msgctxt "an4.191:1.5"
msgid "Tassa te dhammā sotānugatā honti, vacasā paricitā, manasānupekkhitā, diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā. "
msgstr "They’ve followed those teachings by ear, reinforced them by recitation, examined them by the mind, and well comprehended them theoretically. "

#. VAR: muṭṭhassati → muṭṭhassatī (bj)
msgctxt "an4.191:1.6"
msgid "So muṭṭhassati kālaṃ kurumāno aññataraṃ devanikāyaṃ upapajjati. "
msgstr "But they die unmindful and are reborn in one of the orders of gods. "

# NOTE: This is a curious and interesting phrase, see BB’s note. Here I have gone with the comms, though note that I don’t have Norman’s arguments with me. BB’s reading relies on a extremely rare grammatical form (neuter accusative plural in ā), and it just doesn’t read as well to me. I’m also not aware of any passage where the devas are sukhino. The comm interpretation is that the teachings are forgotten in the in-between state (!) and then “float back like shadows in a clear mirror”. (Dhammapadā plavantīti antarābhave nibbattamuṭṭhassatino, yepi pubbe sajjhāyamūlikā vācāparicitabuddhavacanadhammā, te sabbe pasanne ādāse chāyā viya plavanti, pākaṭā hutvā paññāyanti.) To me this makes psychological sense. I also thinks it fits better the structure of the text. To start with, sometimes memory spontaneously comes back. If not, something reminds you. But why would it come back hearing the teaching and not when the gods are speaking directly to you?
#. VAR: plavanti → pilapanti (bj, s1-3, km, pts1)
msgctxt "an4.191:1.7"
msgid "Tassa tattha sukhino dhammapadā plavanti. "
msgstr "Being happy there, passages of the teaching come back to them. "

msgctxt "an4.191:1.8"
msgid "Dandho, bhikkhave, satuppādo; "
msgstr "Memory comes up slowly, "

msgctxt "an4.191:1.9"
msgid "atha so satto khippaṃyeva visesagāmī hoti. "
msgstr "but then that being quickly reaches distinction. "

msgctxt "an4.191:1.10"
msgid "Sotānugatānaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ, vacasā paricitānaṃ, manasānupekkhitānaṃ, diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhānaṃ ayaṃ paṭhamo ānisaṃso pāṭikaṅkho. "
msgstr "This is the first benefit you can expect when the teachings have been followed by ear, reinforced by recitation, examined by the mind, and well comprehended theoretically. "

#. HTML: </p><p>
